My Claude Usage Strategy

Profile: Student · Primary use case: Coding · Usage frequency: Occasional


Recommended Primary Model

Claude Sonnet 5

Why This Model Fits Me


As a student using Claude occasionally for coding, Sonnet 5 offers the best balance of quality, speed, and cost.
It handles everyday coding work — writing functions, debugging, learning new languages — very well.
Opus-tier reasoning isn't needed for most coursework and would just add unnecessary latency and cost.


When to Use Haiku


Quick syntax questions ("what does this error mean?")
Fast one-off snippets, boilerplate, formatting code
Explaining a short block of code line-by-line
Anytime speed matters more than depth


When to Use Sonnet


Your default for almost everything: writing functions, debugging, working through assignments, learning new frameworks, reviewing your own code
Covers 90%+ of typical student coding work


When to Use Opus


Genuinely hard problems: system/architecture design, tricky algorithmic bugs, large multi-file refactors, capstone/thesis-level projects
When you're stuck and Sonnet's answer didn't actually solve it
Reserve for the ~5–10% of tasks that truly need deeper reasoning



